    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Syzygium luzonense improperly are experience allergic reactions due to the presence of essential oils that can cause skin and respiratory sensitization, develop skin irritations such as redness and itching as a result of the plant's sap or essential oils causing dermal contact irritation, induce nausea and vomiting due to gastrointestinal upset caused by the plant's toxic compounds, it causes diarrhea as the body tries to expel the toxins from the Syzygium luzonense, these adverse effects occur because the improper use of Syzygium luzonense can lead to the ingestion of toxic compounds that are not typically found in the plant's edible parts.",
    "uses": "Syzygium luzonense, also known as the Philippine laurel, has been used in traditional medicine to treat various ailments. Its leaves and bark are rich in antioxidants and have been used to reduce inflammation and fight off infections. The plant's extracts have also been studied for their potential anti-diabetic and anti-cancer properties. In addition, the Philippine laurel has been used to treat fever, cough, and digestive issues. Further research is needed to fully understand the medicinal uses and potential benefits of Syzygium luzonense.",
    "taxonomy": "Syzygium luzonense is classified within the family Myrtaceae. It belongs to the genus Syzygium, which is a group of flowering plants native to tropical Asia. The species Syzygium luzonense is specifically found in the Philippines. This classification places Syzygium luzonense in the kingdom Plantae. The species is also known to be closely related to other Syzygium species found in the region.",
    "benefits": "Syzygium luzonense is a species of plant known for its potential health benefits. It is said to have antimicrobial and antioxidant properties, which may help protect against infections and cell damage. The plant is also believed to possess anti-inflammatory properties, which could aid in reducing swelling and pain. Additionally, Syzygium luzonense may have antiviral properties, helping to combat viral infections. Further research is needed to fully understand the extent of its health benefits.",
    "parts": "Syzygium luzonense is a species of tree commonly found in the Philippines and other parts of Southeast Asia. The medicinal parts of Syzygium luzonense include the leaves, bark, and roots, which have been traditionally used to treat various health conditions. The leaves of the tree have been used to treat fever, rheumatism, and other inflammatory diseases. The bark and roots of the tree have been used to treat digestive issues and respiratory problems. The medicinal properties of Syzygium luzonense are still being studied and used in traditional medicine, but more research is needed to fully understand its potential benefits.",
    "intro": "Syzygium luzonense is a species of plant in the family Myrtaceae, commonly known as the Luzon water berry or Luzon syzygium. The plant is valued for its potential health benefits, which include antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties, making it useful in treating various ailments such as fever, cough, and respiratory issues. The bioactive constituents of Syzygium luzonense include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and terpenoids, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. In traditional medicine, the plant is commonly used to make teas, infusions, and extracts, which are also sold as dietary supplements to support immune function and overall well-being."
